1
00:00:00,728 --> 00:00:00,998
Speaker 2: Hey.

2
00:00:00,998 --> 00:00:01,938
Hi, everyone.

3
00:00:02,088 --> 00:00:03,228
Thank you for joining in.

4
00:00:03,798 --> 00:00:08,528
I'm Ananya, and I work as a
GenAI developer advocate at AWS.

5
00:00:09,178 --> 00:00:14,767
My primary role not only relies
on building AI solutions, but also

6
00:00:14,767 --> 00:00:20,378
helping developers and innovators
build and ship their AI products

7
00:00:20,417 --> 00:00:22,157
from prototype to production.

8
00:00:22,657 --> 00:00:24,698
So I'll start with a
small confession today.

9
00:00:25,528 --> 00:00:31,137
I actually built a game, and I assumed
the hardest part of it would be reasoning.

10
00:00:31,907 --> 00:00:39,257
And I had this AI agent running on modern
LLMs, access different tools, load game

11
00:00:39,257 --> 00:00:44,438
state, have retrieval of information
from different sources, and everything

12
00:00:44,438 --> 00:00:46,787
we usually associate with intelligence.

13
00:00:47,507 --> 00:00:50,607
Still, my game failed
eight of the ten times.

14
00:00:51,547 --> 00:00:56,277
At first, I blamed prompting, then I
blamed model, then I blamed architecture,

15
00:00:56,837 --> 00:01:01,057
but after digging into failures, I
discovered something very surprising.

16
00:01:01,837 --> 00:01:04,917
So my agent wasn't making bad decisions.

17
00:01:05,427 --> 00:01:09,247
It was making decisions based
on the bad memories it had.

18
00:01:10,098 --> 00:01:15,597
And that is what my talk is all
about today, where I show how

19
00:01:15,657 --> 00:01:17,487
to make agents more smarter.

20
00:01:18,037 --> 00:01:22,167
How do you make them remember the
right context at the right time?

21
00:01:22,667 --> 00:01:26,687
So to study these memory failures,
I built a Horcrux hunt game.

22
00:01:27,187 --> 00:01:33,567
And if you are familiar with the Harry
Potter series, the objective of Harry

23
00:01:33,577 --> 00:01:38,647
is to find and destroy Horcruxes,
whereas Voldemort's objective is

24
00:01:38,717 --> 00:01:45,257
equally different: to make Harry believe
wrong things and hide the Horcruxes.

25
00:01:46,117 --> 00:01:50,977
So for my game, there are 50 turns
actually, and every turn Harry

26
00:01:50,977 --> 00:01:55,687
gets to collect signals, update
beliefs, and every turn Voldemort

27
00:01:55,727 --> 00:01:58,547
will introduce some uncertainty
through relocations or dis- decoys.

28
00:01:58,547 --> 00:02:00,957
Now, notice something very important.

29
00:02:01,257 --> 00:02:04,117
This problem is not a search problem.

30
00:02:04,717 --> 00:02:07,657
It's how you reduce uncertainty.

31
00:02:08,227 --> 00:02:14,357
So Harry wins by reducing entropy,
and Voldemort wins by increasing it.

32
00:02:15,137 --> 00:02:18,377
That makes memory the central
challenge of this game.

33
00:02:18,877 --> 00:02:25,137
So if Harry forgets useful information
or remembers a false one, the game

34
00:02:25,177 --> 00:02:27,337
is effectively lost on his end.

35
00:02:27,837 --> 00:02:32,787
These are the actual observations
I have from the actual failures.

36
00:02:33,287 --> 00:02:36,867
The interesting thing is that none
of them were reasoning failures.

37
00:02:37,237 --> 00:02:39,267
The model knew how to think.

38
00:02:39,437 --> 00:02:42,257
It simply had the wrong
information available.

39
00:02:43,147 --> 00:02:49,147
For example, Harry destroys a location
that was once valid, but Voldemort

40
00:02:49,157 --> 00:02:51,827
has already moved the Horcrux.

41
00:02:52,247 --> 00:02:53,527
That's stale memory.

42
00:02:54,357 --> 00:03:00,267
Another example where Harry revisits
a location thinking there's a Horcrux,

43
00:03:00,287 --> 00:03:02,607
but it's already confirmed empty.

44
00:03:03,307 --> 00:03:10,497
So the signal existed, but it was buried
under the tokens That's retrieval failure.

45
00:03:11,117 --> 00:03:16,587
And perhaps the most common issue
is that agents remember everything,

46
00:03:17,257 --> 00:03:22,367
which sounds good until context
becomes so large that the generation

47
00:03:22,367 --> 00:03:25,077
becomes slow, expensive, and costly.

48
00:03:26,037 --> 00:03:31,907
So the key lesson here is most
agent failures are because of memory

49
00:03:31,907 --> 00:03:36,347
architecture failures, which are
disguised as reasoning failures.

50
00:03:37,217 --> 00:03:41,547
Now, when people talk about
context windows, they usually

51
00:03:41,627 --> 00:03:43,817
think of them as a storage limit.

52
00:03:44,707 --> 00:03:52,187
I think of them as compounding tax because
you have 50 turns, and every turn you are

53
00:03:52,347 --> 00:03:55,037
replaying the context again and again.

54
00:03:55,637 --> 00:04:01,277
Now, imagine reading an entire book,
but every time you want to turn a page,

55
00:04:01,287 --> 00:04:03,207
you are rereading the whole book again.

56
00:04:03,707 --> 00:04:08,717
That's effectively what many
agents in production do today.

57
00:04:09,517 --> 00:04:15,427
As the game progresses in my example,
the context is growing, latency is

58
00:04:15,427 --> 00:04:19,257
growing, therefore, the cost also grows.

59
00:04:19,877 --> 00:04:24,677
And when you add multiple agents,
the problem becomes worse.

60
00:04:25,177 --> 00:04:30,637
This is why memory design becomes
a scaling problem long before

61
00:04:30,647 --> 00:04:32,267
it becomes a reasoning problem.

62
00:04:33,177 --> 00:04:37,677
So now I want to introduce a slightly
different way of thinking about

63
00:04:37,737 --> 00:04:40,307
memory through information theory.

64
00:04:40,867 --> 00:04:44,657
So at the start of the game,
Harry knows almost nothing.

65
00:04:44,737 --> 00:04:49,667
All 15 locations that he has to
search the Horcrux is equally likely

66
00:04:50,167 --> 00:04:52,167
Uncertainty is at its maximum.

67
00:04:52,207 --> 00:04:53,417
Entropy is high.

68
00:04:54,327 --> 00:05:00,487
But as and when turns keep on playing,
the game is being played, observations

69
00:05:00,747 --> 00:05:03,947
arrive, and entropy should decrease.

70
00:05:04,787 --> 00:05:10,137
The agent becomes more confident, more
focused, more certain that a Horcrux

71
00:05:10,197 --> 00:05:12,257
is hidden at a particular location.

72
00:05:12,757 --> 00:05:15,467
But Voldemort actively injects entropy.

73
00:05:15,877 --> 00:05:21,057
Every relocation and every decoy
increases the uncertainty in the game.

74
00:05:21,557 --> 00:05:27,897
This led me to the realization that memory
architecture is really entropy management.

75
00:05:28,417 --> 00:05:33,047
Every memory decision answers
just one question: Does this help

76
00:05:33,127 --> 00:05:35,627
reduce uncertainty or increase it?

77
00:05:36,567 --> 00:05:40,457
And that's the lens we'll use
for the rest of the talk today.

78
00:05:40,957 --> 00:05:46,147
So after studying the failures, I ended up
with a simple three-layered memory model.

79
00:05:46,647 --> 00:05:48,897
Layer one is working memory.

80
00:05:49,587 --> 00:05:52,027
This is what the LLM sees currently.

81
00:05:52,057 --> 00:05:57,867
It's expensive, it's limited,
it's precious, but it also helps

82
00:05:57,877 --> 00:05:59,987
finding the current context.

83
00:06:00,487 --> 00:06:06,517
Layer two is retrieval memory,
where the information what agent

84
00:06:06,527 --> 00:06:09,347
can access is when it is needed.

85
00:06:10,117 --> 00:06:12,967
Not everything, only the
relevant information.

86
00:06:13,467 --> 00:06:19,477
And layer three is the persistent
memory, the long-term memory that records

87
00:06:19,517 --> 00:06:22,377
everything the agent has ever experienced.

88
00:06:22,537 --> 00:06:27,657
The most important idea here is
to separate the responsibilities.

89
00:06:27,727 --> 00:06:29,547
Each layer has its job.

90
00:06:30,347 --> 00:06:34,507
The first one gives the current
context, the second one gives the

91
00:06:34,517 --> 00:06:39,057
retrieval context, and the third
one saves information over time.

92
00:06:39,747 --> 00:06:43,417
And when these layers start doing
each other's job, your system

93
00:06:43,417 --> 00:06:45,097
becomes expensive and fragile.

94
00:06:45,647 --> 00:06:51,037
But if they stick to their lanes,
that's when your system is optimal So

95
00:06:51,037 --> 00:06:53,167
my first optimization is very simple.

96
00:06:53,727 --> 00:06:56,217
Stop sending everything to an LLM.

97
00:06:56,217 --> 00:07:02,487
Most agent systems treat context
as historical transcript, but the

98
00:07:02,497 --> 00:07:04,377
model doesn't need your history.

99
00:07:04,837 --> 00:07:06,377
It needs state.

100
00:07:06,807 --> 00:07:11,267
So instead of sending information
of all the 50 turns, observations

101
00:07:11,267 --> 00:07:16,457
of all the 50 turns, I send a
compressed representation, a small

102
00:07:16,507 --> 00:07:22,607
belief map, valid actions, remaining
budget, the information of cooldowns.

103
00:07:23,597 --> 00:07:28,607
And the result is ninety-seven
percent token compression.

104
00:07:29,107 --> 00:07:30,847
But here's the surprising part.

105
00:07:31,427 --> 00:07:35,587
Performance also improved because
now the model has stopped getting

106
00:07:35,587 --> 00:07:41,707
distracted by irrelevant details,
and it is becoming better at context.

107
00:07:42,587 --> 00:07:45,247
The second one was probably
the biggest breakthrough.

108
00:07:45,817 --> 00:07:51,287
So instead of asking the LLMs to
remember probabilities, we let the

109
00:07:51,287 --> 00:07:53,547
maths remember the probabilities.

110
00:07:54,377 --> 00:08:00,837
There's a belief map which updates outside
of the model, so the LLM receives only

111
00:08:00,837 --> 00:08:03,347
the output which has highest probability.

112
00:08:03,927 --> 00:08:10,457
For example, instead of sending remaining
information and also history information

113
00:08:10,457 --> 00:08:17,087
from 50 turns, the model sees the next
probable location is Hogwarts with

114
00:08:17,087 --> 00:08:22,307
thirty-four percent probability or
Chamber of Secr-Secrets with fifty percent

115
00:08:22,307 --> 00:08:26,697
probability Eight to 15 tokens, not 5,000.

116
00:08:27,197 --> 00:08:29,377
That's the powerful design pattern.

117
00:08:30,367 --> 00:08:33,567
And whenever memory can be
represented as structured state,

118
00:08:34,087 --> 00:08:36,987
use structure instead of language.

119
00:08:37,917 --> 00:08:42,127
Because language is
expensive, math is cheap.

120
00:08:43,087 --> 00:08:49,427
The next insight was not that every
decision deserves the same memory budget.

121
00:08:50,247 --> 00:08:53,377
Not every decision is worth an LLM call.

122
00:08:54,267 --> 00:08:58,767
Sometimes the answer is obvious,
so why do we need to spend tokens?

123
00:08:58,767 --> 00:09:01,097
Why even call an LLM for that matter?

124
00:09:01,597 --> 00:09:07,677
When uncertainty is genuinely high,
that's when richer context becomes

125
00:09:07,737 --> 00:09:12,637
valuable, and we definitely need
to call an LLM for that reason.

126
00:09:12,647 --> 00:09:16,997
We route the memory dynamically
based on the entropy.

127
00:09:17,967 --> 00:09:21,007
So if there's low
uncertainty, use heuristics.

128
00:09:21,537 --> 00:09:25,117
If the uncertainty is medium,
use compressed memory.

129
00:09:25,657 --> 00:09:29,157
And if the uncertainty is
high, use richer retrieval.

130
00:09:29,987 --> 00:09:35,007
For example, if Harry is after destroying
the Horcruxes and he finds a particular

131
00:09:35,007 --> 00:09:39,967
Horcrux in a location, the obvious
action by Voldemort would be either

132
00:09:39,987 --> 00:09:44,567
to hide that particular Horcrux in a
different location, that is relocate,

133
00:09:45,117 --> 00:09:47,537
or maybe deploy a decoy instead.

134
00:09:48,137 --> 00:09:50,897
So this particular action is obvious.

135
00:09:50,897 --> 00:09:56,717
We don't need to, again and again,
take an LLM call for this reason.

136
00:09:57,557 --> 00:09:58,767
So what happens as a result?

137
00:09:59,357 --> 00:10:03,117
The system spends memory
only where it matters.

138
00:10:04,107 --> 00:10:06,667
And the final one, the persistent memory.

139
00:10:07,497 --> 00:10:12,897
So this layer solves the problem many
agent systems generally struggle with.

140
00:10:13,237 --> 00:10:18,017
Like, how do you remember everything
without sending everything to an LLM?

141
00:10:18,887 --> 00:10:21,357
The answer is persistence.

142
00:10:22,077 --> 00:10:28,237
Store abundantly, retrieve selectively,
present to the LLM minimally.

143
00:10:28,957 --> 00:10:30,617
Everything lives in persistence.

144
00:10:30,617 --> 00:10:35,237
You will save all the information,
but only the relevant information

145
00:10:35,247 --> 00:10:37,137
gets passed on to the LLM.

146
00:10:37,817 --> 00:10:40,607
This prevents two common failure modes.

147
00:10:40,967 --> 00:10:45,687
First, you do not overload
the model with whole history.

148
00:10:46,437 --> 00:10:50,967
And second, you forget
everything between turns.

149
00:10:51,467 --> 00:10:54,787
So persistent memory gives
you the third option.

150
00:10:55,287 --> 00:10:58,567
So if you want to remember just
one architecture diagram from

151
00:10:58,567 --> 00:11:00,627
this talk, let it be this one.

152
00:11:01,417 --> 00:11:03,727
Notice where the LLM sits.

153
00:11:04,177 --> 00:11:06,087
It's actually a very small component.

154
00:11:06,137 --> 00:11:08,847
Most of the intelligence
happens outside the model.

155
00:11:08,847 --> 00:11:14,467
The belief management, the constraint
solving, entropy calculations,

156
00:11:14,507 --> 00:11:16,687
persistence, compression of tokens.

157
00:11:17,537 --> 00:11:20,237
The LLM is not the memory system.

158
00:11:20,527 --> 00:11:25,837
The LLM rather consumes the memory
system, and that architectural

159
00:11:25,837 --> 00:11:27,947
distinction actually changes everything.

160
00:11:28,447 --> 00:11:30,417
So now let's look at the outcomes.

161
00:11:30,977 --> 00:11:35,877
The same game, the same agents, and
having the same reasoning capabilities.

162
00:11:36,377 --> 00:11:38,907
Only the memory architecture has changed.

163
00:11:39,407 --> 00:11:44,257
Now, the results are dramatic, where we
have ninety-seven percent fewer tokens,

164
00:11:44,647 --> 00:11:50,117
seventy-five percent lower latency, and
more than eighty percent cost reduction.

165
00:11:50,617 --> 00:11:53,927
Most importantly, the win
rate has also doubled.

166
00:11:54,427 --> 00:12:00,287
This is why I argue memory deserves
more attention than model selection.

167
00:12:00,787 --> 00:12:05,157
Often, the biggest performance
gain come from memory architecture

168
00:12:05,577 --> 00:12:09,797
and not larger models So let me
leave you with five principles.

169
00:12:10,247 --> 00:12:15,787
The first, an LLM should consume
memory, not produce memory.

170
00:12:16,687 --> 00:12:21,207
Second, match the memory
depth to decision difficulty.

171
00:12:21,707 --> 00:12:26,957
Third, compression belongs at
boundary, not inside the model.

172
00:12:27,457 --> 00:12:32,897
Fourth, persist abundantly,
retrieve selectively, and

173
00:12:32,897 --> 00:12:35,187
present minimally to an LLM.

174
00:12:35,687 --> 00:12:41,627
Finally, less context often leads to
better decisions because attention

175
00:12:41,627 --> 00:12:44,997
is a scarce resource, even for LLMs.

176
00:12:45,497 --> 00:12:51,677
So the systems that win won't necessarily
be the ones with biggest context windows.

177
00:12:52,177 --> 00:12:57,337
They'll be the ones that know
what to remember and what not to

178
00:12:57,367 --> 00:13:00,537
remember So I end where I started.

179
00:13:01,417 --> 00:13:06,667
My agent had reasoning, it had
tools, it had retrieval, and still

180
00:13:06,667 --> 00:13:11,917
it failed because intelligence
wasn't the bottleneck, memory was.

181
00:13:12,817 --> 00:13:17,697
And as we build increasingly
agentic systems, memory

182
00:13:17,787 --> 00:13:19,697
becomes infrastructure for us.

183
00:13:20,197 --> 00:13:24,757
And the question no longer remains: How
much context can I fit and remember?

184
00:13:25,257 --> 00:13:30,537
The question becomes: What
information deserves to be remembered?

185
00:13:31,037 --> 00:13:34,537
Because your agents don't fail
because they cannot reason.

186
00:13:35,307 --> 00:13:39,677
They fail because they
remember the wrong things.

187
00:13:40,177 --> 00:13:45,747
With that, I say the future of
agents isn't bigger context windows.

188
00:13:46,247 --> 00:13:48,597
It's better memory architectures.

189
00:13:49,407 --> 00:13:51,017
Thank you so much for listening.

